Date:  0/0/1937
Source:  Pakeha & Maori
Author:  COWAN
Vol / Page:  1/4
Edition:
Quote:  They unloaded a packhorse and brought in a dozen bags of bush fungus, the hakeke of the Maori, which grows on old stumps and logs so plentifully. Now fungus was always a marketable commodity, for the China market; it brought sixpence a pound or more from the storekeepers, who sold it to the town dealers; it went to make a choice soup for rich Chinese.
